Should I be bored at a startup?
text:
I'm a technical co-founder, haven't built anything since February, no users use what I built, no sales have been made, we keep pushing in the same direction that brings no results.

In my spare time I've started some side projects that got MRR from day one. (you can see how that's going in my post history)

Is my CEO in the way? His focus is raising (and investors want MRR), it's never sales or product. I'm really bored, we have another dev that also has nothing to do because there is nothing to be done. We just go around in circles tackling the same unsolvable problem that potentially can't even be solved with tech.

Potential customers say they're interested until it comes time to buy.

But my CEO wants to delay the process of asking for payment AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.

Instead of testing willingness to pay by:

"Oh hey you're interested, sign here: "

We instead suggest a 3-6 MONTH UNPAID PILOT WITH UNCLEAR BENEFITS FOR THE CLIENT. They even ask: "What do we get out of this?".

This isn't traction, it's confusion.

Am I taking crazy pills here? I got into this to make money, not fuck around.

Seems like everything I'm told/asked to do is zero-benefit work with zero leverage. Such as preparing a tech internship program for summer. What the actual fuck, where are the sales?

Sorry for the rant.
